<worksheet xml:id="worksheet-vectors">

<title>Discovery guide</title>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-directed-line-segments">

	<task><p>
		Plot points <m>P(1,2)</m> and <m>Q(3,-1)</m> in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
		Draw an arrow from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>.
		This arrow is called the
		<term>directed line segment</term>
		<idx><h>directed line segment</h></idx>
		<m>\abray{PQ}</m>.
	</p></task>

	<task xml:id="activity-vectors-directed-line-segments-components"><p>
		Fill in the
		<term>components</term>
		<idx><h>components</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vector</h><h>components</h></idx>
		for this directed line segment:
		<m>\abray{PQ} = (\Delta x, \Delta y) = (<fillin characters="5" />,<fillin characters="5" />)</m>.
	</p></task>

	<task><p>
		On the same axes you've been working on, plot the point <m>R</m> that has the same coordinates as the components of <m>\abray{PQ}</m>,
		and draw the directed line segment <m>\abray{OR}</m> where <m>O</m> is the origin.
		What do you notice about this arrow?
	</p></task>

	<task><p>
		This <q>common</q> arrow for <m>\abray{PQ}</m> and <m>\abray{OR}</m>
		(and all arrows in the <m>xy</m>-plane just like it)
		is called a <term>vector</term><idx><h>vector</h></idx>.
		Let's label this vector <m>\uvec{v}</m>.
		Draw another <q>copy</q> of <m>\uvec{v}</m> so that its
		<term>initial point</term>
		<idx><h>initial point</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vector</h><h>initial point</h></idx>
		is <m>S(-2,1)</m>.
		What will be the
		<term>terminal point</term>
		<idx><h>terminal point</h></idx>
		<idx><h>vector</h><h>terminal point</h></idx>
		for this copy of <m>\uvec{v}</m>?
	</p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-geom-vec-add">

	<task><p>
		Draw the vector <m>\uvec{u} = (2,3)</m> with its initial point at <m>P(1,1)</m>.
		Label this vector on your diagram,
		and label its terminal point as <m>Q</m>.
		Now draw the vector <m>\uvec{v} = (3,-1)</m> with its initial point at <m>Q</m>.
		Label this vector on your diagram, and label this second terminal point as <m>R</m>.
		Draw in vector <m>\uvec{w}</m> corresponding to <m>\abray{PR}</m>.
	</p></task>

	<task>

		<p>
		Compute the components of <m>\uvec{w}</m> using a <m>(\Delta x, \Delta y)</m> calculation between its initial and terminal points in your diagram,
		similarly to <xref ref="activity-vectors-directed-line-segments-components" />.
		</p>

		<p>
		Looking at the components of <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m>,
		what do you notice about the components of <m>\uvec{w}</m>?
		Based on this, we should call <m>\uvec{w}</m> the <fillin characters="3" /> of <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m>,
		and write <m>\uvec{w} = \uvec{u}<fillin characters="2" />\uvec{v}</m>.
		</p>

	</task>

	<task>

		<statement><p>
			Now work in the reverse order:
			on the same diagram you've been working on,
			draw <m>\uvec{v}</m> starting at <m>P</m>,
			then draw <m>\uvec{u}</m> starting at that terminal point.
			Where did the second terminal point end up?
			Turn this into a rule for vector algebra: <fillin characters="12" />.
		</p></statement>

		<hint><p>
			Your rule should be about the different ways to combine <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m> that you've explored so far in this activity.
		</p></hint>

	</task>

	<task><p>
		What shape do the four vectors on the outside make?
		And what is <m>\abray{PR}</m> relative to that shape (geometrically)?
	</p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-zero-vec">

	<task><p> How should you draw the vector <m>\zerovec = (0,0)</m>? </p></task>

	<task><p>
		What happens if you draw <m>\zerovec</m> tail-to-head or head-to-tail with another vector
		(as in <xref ref="activity-vectors-geom-vec-add" />)?
		Turn this into a rule for vector algebra: <fillin characters="12" />.
	</p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-neg-vec">

	<introduction><p> We would reasonably expect <m>\uvec{v} + (-\uvec{v}) = \zerovec</m> in vector algebra. </p></introduction>

	<task><p>
		Draw a geometric representation of this rule on a set of axes for <m>\uvec{v} = (1,2)</m>
		(use the origin as the initial point for <m>\uvec{v}</m>).
	</p></task>

	<task><p> What should the components of <m>-\uvec{v}</m> be? </p></task>

	<task><p> On the same set of axes as before, draw <m>-\uvec{v}</m> with its initial point at the origin. </p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-diff-vec-between-heads">

	<introduction><p>
		Draw an arbitrary vector in the plane, and label it <m>\uvec{u}</m>.
		Then draw another arbitrary vector with its initial point at the terminal point of <m>\uvec{u}</m>
		(but maybe have this new vector head off in a new direction).
		Label this second vector <m>\uvec{v}</m>.
		Now draw in the sum vector <m>\uvec{w} = \uvec{u} + \uvec{v}</m>,
		similarly to
		<xref ref="activity-vectors-geom-vec-add" />.
	</p></introduction>

	<task><p> Which of your three vectors represents <m>\uvec{w} - \uvec{u}</m>? </p></task>

	<task><p> Draw in another vector for <m>\uvec{u} - \uvec{w}</m>. </p></task>

	<task><p> What is the point of this activity? </p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-scalar-mul">

	<task>

		<p>
		Draw a representative diagram for the vector sum <m>\uvec{v} + \uvec{v}</m> using <m>\uvec{v} = (1,2)</m>
		(start with the first initial point at the origin).
		What are the components of this sum vector?
		</p>

		<p>
		From both the geometry of what you've drawn,
		and the result for the components of the sum vector <m>\uvec{v} + \uvec{v}</m>,
		do you think it is reasonable to write <m>2 \uvec{v}</m> to mean <m>\uvec{v} + \uvec{v}</m>?
		</p>

	</task>

	<task><p>
		Now draw each of the following, and determine their components:
		<m>3 \uvec{v}</m>, <m>-2 \uvec{v}</m>, <m>\frac{1}{2} \uvec{v}</m>, <m>-\frac{5}{4} \uvec{v}</m>.
	</p></task>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-scalar-mul-distrib"><p>
	Draw an arbitrary representative diagram for <m>\uvec{w} = \uvec{u} + \uvec{v}</m>
	(similarly to how you started <xref ref="activity-vectors-diff-vec-between-heads" />).
	On the same set of axes, draw a diagram for <m>2 \uvec{u} + 2 \uvec{v}</m>,
	and compare with <m>2 \uvec{w}</m>.
	Express what you've discovered as a rule of vector algebra,
	with <m>2</m> replaced by variable <m>k</m>:
	<fillin characters="12" />.
</p></activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-standard-basis"><p>
	On a set of <m>xy</m>-axes, draw the
	<term>standard basis vectors</term><idx><h>standard</h><h>basis</h></idx><idx><h>basis</h><h>standard</h></idx><idx><h>vector</h><h>standard basis</h></idx>:
	<m>\uvec{e}_1 = (1,0)</m> and <m>\uvec{e}_2 = (0,1)</m>,
	along with the vector <m>\uvec{v} = (5,2)</m>.
	Then draw a geometric representation of <m>\uvec{v}</m> as a
	<term>linear combination</term><idx><h>linear</h><h>combination</h></idx>
	<m>\uvec{v} = 5 \uvec{e}_1 + 2 \uvec{e}_2</m>.
</p></activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-intro-3dim">

	<introduction><p>
		All the vectors we've encountered so far are <term>two-dimensional vectors</term>.
		Let's bump everything up a dimension.
	</p></introduction>

	<task xml:id="activity-vectors-intro-3dim-draw"><p>
		Using <m>\uvec{u} = (1,1,0)</m> and <m>\uvec{v} = (1,-1,2)</m>,
		draw the following on a set of <m>xyz</m>-axes:
		<m>\uvec{u}</m>, <m>\uvec{v}</m>, <m>\uvec{u} + \uvec{v}</m>, <m>-\uvec{u}</m>, <m>\uvec{v} - \uvec{u}</m>, <m>2 \uvec{v}</m>.
	</p></task>

	<task><p> Now compute the components of each of the vectors from the previous part of this activity. </p></task>

</activity>

<activity>

	<prelude><p> We can't draw pictures of <m>n</m>-dimensional vectors if <m>n>3</m>, but we can do all the same algebra. </p></prelude>

	<statement><p>
		Complete the following vector algebra formulas.
		<ul>
			<li> <m>(u_1,u_2,\dotsc,u_n) + (v_1,v_2,\dotsc,v_n) = <fillin characters="15" /></m> </li>
			<li> <m>(u_1,u_2,\dotsc,u_n) - (v_1,v_2,\dotsc,v_n) = <fillin characters="15" /></m> </li>
			<li> <m>-(v_1,v_2,\dotsc,v_n) = <fillin characters="15" /></m> </li>
			<li> <m> k(v_1,v_2,\dotsc,v_n) = <fillin characters="15" /></m> </li>
			<li> <m>\uvec{0} = <fillin characters="15" /></m> </li>
		</ul>
	</p></statement>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-other-displacements">

	<prelude><p>
		We can use vectors to represent other kinds of <q>displacements</q> besides position displacements.
		Vectors can be used to represent change between states of any collection of related variables.
	</p></prelude>

	<statement>

		<p>
		An investor sinks $10,000 into stock in each of companies A, B, C, and D.
		After a year,
		the various items in her portfolio have the following values:
		company A, $10,475;
		company B, $11,240;
		company C, $9,756;
		company D, $10,054.
		</p>

		<p>
		Represent the <q>displacement</q> in the collection of values of the investor's holdings,
		from initial state
		<me> (A,B,C,D) = (10000, 10000, 10000, 10000) </me>
		to terminal state
		<me> (A,B,C,D) = (10475, 11240, 9756, 10054) </me>
		as a four-dimensional vector.
		</p>

	</statement>

</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-vectors-col-vecs">

	<introduction><p>
		If we write two-dimensional vectors in the form
		<m>\uvec{u} = \left[\begin{smallmatrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \end{smallmatrix}\right]</m>,
		instead of the form <m>\uvec{u} = (u_1,u_2)</m>,
		then we can use matrix algebra to do computations with vectors.
	</p></introduction>

	<task><p> Does each rule of vector algebra that we've discovered today have a counterpart rule in matrix algebra? </p></task>

	<task><p>
		Will the same be true for the algebra of higher-dimensional vectors?
		(That is, if we consider using <m>n\times 1</m> column matrices to represent <m>n</m>-dimensional vectors?)
	</p></task>

</activity>

</worksheet>
